descript.abstract: The points represent 2012 postmile locations from the TSN database. These points are locked, roughly, every two miles of the route and calibrated. Bing imagery was used to locate landmarks between the scales of 1:10,000 to 1:1,500.
descript.purpose: This file is a representation of the 2012 postmile locations found in the Transportation System Network (TSN) database from the California Department of Transportation (Caltrans) Traffic Accident Surveillance and Analysis System (TASAS) branch. Additional routes were edited between 1/30/12 - 7/1/13 to include some route edits including the Brawley bypass.
descript.supplinf: This is only a representation of postmile locations along the California highway system and should not be used to interpret anything other than to display approximate geographic postmile locations.

attr.attrdef: Route feature unique ID, indicates the route number, date, and alignment.
Indicates the number of a route

A single-digit alpha code attached to the route as a suffix to identify special situations where there are parallel roads with the same route number operating simultaneously. S = Supplemental, U = Unrelinquished, Z = Budgeted or Unconstructed.
Indicates route alignment: L = Left, R = Right.

A numerical value applied to a route segment sharing common postmile identifiers. The ORDER_ID changes wherever the postmiles add or drop a prefix, suffix, intersects a county line, or the route has a break.
An abbreviated California county code.

A single-digit alpha code attached to the postmile as a prefix to indicate changes in highway alignment. C = Commercial lanes, D = Duplicate postmile at meandering county line, G = Reposting of duplicate postmile at end of a route, H = Realignment of D mileage, L = Overlapping postmile values, M = Realignment of R mileage, N = Realigment of M mileage, R = First realignment, S = Spur, T = Temporary connection.
An indication of alignment where the route alignments are independent. R = Right alignment, L = Left alignment.
A prominent natural or man-made object with a specific assigned postmile value. These discriptions are used to determine distance, bearing, or location of a route.

A numeric value based on the mileage measured from the beginning of a route or from a county line. The postmile, when used in combination with the district, county, and route, makes each location of the state highway system unique. The BEG_PM refers to the postmile value at the beginning of the route segment identified in the TSN and usually originating at the landmark described.
Refers to calibration point location quality level: Quality 1 points are fixed, Quality 3 points are floating.
Equation point. This is a field from TSN and generally indicates locations where two different postmiles reference the same location on a route.

The measure value on the line feature of the corresponding route in miles from the beginning of the route. M-values are used to measure the distance along a line feature and indicate postmile locations relative to a route in ArcMap.
The longitude of the postmile location in Decimal Degrees.
The latitude of the postmile location in Decimal Degrees.

The End Odometer. Each route has an absolute odometer measured in miles calculated from the postmiles that identify measures along the route from the beginning to the end of the route. The odometers are used for calibration purposes and to assist in identifying postmile locations along a route. The END_ODO identifies the odometer value of the corresponding END_PM for the location.
attr.attrdefs: Calculated by the Caltrans Office of Data Analysis and GIS

attr.attrdef: A numeric value based on the mileage measured from the beginning of a route or from a county line. The postmile, when used in combination with the district, county, and route, makes each location of the state highway system unique. The END_PM refers to the postmile value at the end of the route segment identified in the TSN and usually originating at the landmark described.
Feature geometry
Number corresponding to the Caltrans district of the identifed landmark. Caltrans consists of 12 Districts statewide.
Five Highway Groups: R = Independent alignment - right, L = Independent alignment - left, D = Divided highway, U = Undivided highway, X = Unconstructed highway.

An incorporated municipality with definite boundaries and legal powers set forth in a charter granted by the state. An abbreviated city code is indicated when a portion of a route is within the limits of a city.
Effective date. This is the date which the segment at this location became part of the State Highway System.

The Beginning Odometer. Each route has an absolute odometer measured in miles calculated from the postmiles that identify measures along the route from the beginning to the end of the route. The odometers are used for calibration purposes and to assist in identifying postmile locations along a route. The BEG_ODO identifies the odometer value of the corresponding BEG_PM for the location.
attr.attrdefs: Calculated by the Caltrans Office of Data Analysis and GIS

attr.attrdef: The type of segment reference in the TSN. TSN defines three postmile location types: H = Highway, I = Intersection, R = Ramp. A Highway segment has a different beginning and ending postmile and a length. An Intersection is actually a point and has the same beginning and ending postmile. Ramps locations should not occur in this dataset.
